fields.description:
This is a Regulatory item Due Jan 1, 2016.

Summary:
Regulatory Reform is changing the way routine home care is paid by creating two rates. A higher rate for the first 60 days of care and a lower rate for the remaining days of care. If a patient re-admits to hospice care from the same or different hospice the days carry over unless there is a gap of more than 60 days.

Background:
Starting on January 1, Consolo will need to know how many days each patient has been on hospice care with the current or former hospice. This information can be calculated from the Eligibilty HIQA. This former hospice history is necessary to be able to calculate the correct revenue for patients going forward. As of Jan 1 we will need to perform a calculation to arrive at the correct rate or add another column in our Rates Catalog to store the two different rates. A calculation may be better since payers do not want us to split this onto a separate claim line when the rate changes mid-month.

For example: 
Patient was on service for 40 days, off service 70 days, then admits to a Consolo hospice on Dec 1. This patient's day count was re-set to zero on Dec 1 because of the gap in care, but he has used 31 days of the first 60 days as of Jan 1. Consolo will bill at the old standard RHC rate for Dec 1-31 and then the higher RHC rate from Jan 1-29 and then the lower RHC rate for Jan 30th and 31st. February and beyond will be at the lower rate. Medicare wants all 31 days for January on one line with the rate calculated appropriately.

Side Note:
We will encourage all clients to sign up for Eligibilty but since we charge extra for it, we can't force them to do it. Unfortunately we probably need to offer a place for clients who don't use our Eligiblity module to enter the "prior days". Entering it in the admission makes sense. We could add a field called "Prior Medicare Days". The field could default to 0 and then if someone runs a HIQA it would auto-update to the correct number and if they don't want to run a HIQA they can edit it manually. When a person re-admits, a new HIQA would be run to auto-update the information in current and past admissions.

Requirements:
Calculate from HIQA data and place into the Admission in a new Field called "Prior Medicare Days"
Calculate from HIQA data and place into the Admission a new field called "Medicare Gap"
Allow a user to override the figures when there is no HIQA or it is not accurate (allow an editable field)
Calculate from past Consolo admission and Consolo days used if there is no gap in care between admission and discharge (discharge/readmit next day; discharge readmit same day).
fields.summary: Number of Prior Days Used and Gap in Days of Care-14678

fields.description:
The billing team has identified an issue with the medication fill records. Medication fill records are not showing on claims when the patient's office has changed. 
It was first identified last month. Here is the communication:
"Has anybody said anything about med fills not showing up on 817s? I have an 817 that popped up for a patient. When I compared it to the original, the med fills are all gone. The original claim has them on there. I checked the med fills for the patient and there haven't been any reversals entered. This is the first claim I have noticed it on so I am not sure that it is anything more than a fluke thing. The only thing that changed was the med fills being removed. All of the clinical visits and the hospice care lines are the same. 

817: https://compassionate.consoloservices.com/claims/1934315 
812: https://compassionate.consoloservices.com/claims/1905431 "

Example from yesterday (12/2/15):
https://doctorshospice.consoloservices.com/patients/193313/care_level_changes 
https://doctorshospice.consoloservices.com/patients/193313/medication_fills 

There is a Redmine ticket (#14830) associated to this that has not been prioritized.
fields.summary: Medication Fill Records not on Claims - Issue 2

comments.body:
There is actually nothing wrong with what is happening right now.

Patient is provided care under Office A.
Medications are accepted and stored under Office A.
After billing has occurred, someone decides "Oh, this patient should be in Office B".
User enters care level change out-of-sequence that changes some part of the patient date range to Office B.
Historical Data is not changed; it maintains historical accuracy with the way data was at the time of entry.
Claims get changed; a new claim is created for Office B.

Office B has no medication fills, ergo, no medication fills.

So someone needs to decide what happens from here, as the software is functioning as designed and any departure is going to be a new feature.

Do you ignore the office when adding the med fills onto the claim? You might send the wrong data. We also currently do not have medication fill data on the billing verification report. If we do this, then at no point will we be able to add medication fills onto the report and expect it to work. The same thing goes for any other report.

Do you change historical data? That seems unwise and goes against the purpose of having historical data being preserved.

Do you duplicate data into the new office? That gives an inflated sense of what was prescribed.

I agree.  This is more of a feature than a bug.  My first thought is to ignore the office and just follow the patient for that date of service, but some sites will discharge and readmit to a different office on the same day and if meds are filled that day we can't/shouldn't put the same meds on both claims.

Good to clarify, thanks.

These 3 choices are the options that I can see, so I don't know what to do otherwise. Maybe you can look for multiple offices if the claim is an adjustment by including the original claim's office, but that still seems like it violates what you stipulate about multiple offices, and in certain situations it certainly will get too many medication fills.
need more details, please

I notice when the care level is edited and the office is changed Clinical Charts change the office associated with those charts. 

Isn't this similar to what we are describing here that the Med Fill Record data should reflect the Office associated with the Care Level based on the date of the Fill.

I am fine with that, however, Teena has brought up the issue that when you have same-day-readmits into a different office, sometimes you actually must differentiate between who gave what medication to the patient. Doing so will sometimes overwrite data with incorrect values.

fields.description:
On the services / pharmacy screen, have a yes/no flag that all asks if prescription e-routing is enabled for this pharmacy.  If the agency chooses to enable, they must then look up the pharmacy from the master list and thereby save the master list id (SPI) to the services pharmacy record.  

Going forward, when new pharmacies are added, the look up function should source the list from the master list and then "auto-connect" the services record w/ the master list record via SPI.  If the new pharmacy isn't found, the agency can still add the service but they will have to later "enable" e-prescription routing once the pharmacy has been added to the master list by surescripts.  We should add an automatic function that generates an alert when a pharmacy is added after not being found in the directory so that they can be routed to surescripts quickly

fields.description:
Current process is from core directly to HospiScript for a medication message. Need an estimate to move it from core to webmethods as the delivery mechanism. Jordan has estimated the core portion in JIRA ticket CD-1628. Let me know what questions you have. 

Moving this up in the queue for Compassus.
fields.summary: Estimate Moving Medication Message for HospiScript from Core to Webmethods

comments.body: Can someone send me the sample post xml / json and the their format if they have one? Are we delivering this via a http post to an endpoint, writing to a customer SFTP location, or do we need to add a new SFTP location on our WM sftp server?

Expected Workflow: Jordan sends an XML message to webmethods.  Webmethods receives XML and leaves it in the same structure, posts to an HTTPS endpoint

Assumption: We don't have to map the original structure to a new structure.  
Assumption, we already have credentials to connect with. 

Estimate,  4h-8h (the extra 4 hours is my buffer to account that certificates and ssl are always dodgy to accomplish the first time). 
Also, if I have to map the xml to a new structure that could use some of that extra time. 

Overall, shouldn't be more than 1 day

Yes, there will be some mapping. I envision this like the ADT in that there should be a "superset" of data and we'll pick and choose from that based on the needs of the PBM (Pharmacy Benefit Manager). The only one implemented today is HospiScript and we know what their connection info is, but there will be others. I've asked a couple of others for their specs to see if there are additional fields of data to add.

Also, we have the HospiScript spec that was used when this was implemented. I will attach that here unless they have updated documentation (which I have requested).
gave colleen the estimate

Can someone send me the http url and credentials for hospiscript that we're supposed to send this file to? 

Are there different test / production credentials?

Yes, there are different test and production credentials.  I can verify the test credentials with HospiScript when I notify them that we are going to try to move them to webmethods. As for production, can you "see" where we are posting today?
Brian K gave me the xml that is currently used.  Can I move forward with that or will there be changes that I should wait for?

We want to be able to implement the ADT with a few other PBMs who have been waiting for this functionality. I have documentation from one of them and am waiting for some info from another. We wanted to be able to add any additional fields to the superset.
What is blocking this?
This us related to CD-1628
Once I have the final XML structure, I'm good to go.  I was under the impression that the specs of it were still in process per CD-1628

The problem of 30+ duplicates being shown was fixed months ago. But it was fixed with an ugly hack, not by addressing the root problem (which is that our current med system requires NDC). comments.body: I would like to see requirements documented on this before we start.

That's good. I have talked about this to Teena and some of the other billers, but it's good to have it somewhere.

This application will:

* Have its own url (e.g. https://billing.consoloservices.com)
* Will not restrict content by-agency, it will restrict by-user-credentials. If the user can see 5 agencies, it sees 5 agencies of data.
* Will duplicate all functionality on the "Claims Summary" or main claim index page, including all operations at the bottom of the screen.
* Will provide a method of generating claims in the by-user-credentials pattern, rather than by-agency pattern.

These simple things will allow us to get 75% of the work a biller does on a day-to-day basis done on a single screen. Well, when you combine that with NOE automation and claims status inquiries.

fields.description:
Larger Hospices.. multi-state, multi-time zone is reporting this issue in some reports...  I have asked the support team to identify a list of the reports and examples.
Advantage, Umbrella, etc.. 

Umbrella Hospice has run into a problem when running reports due to differences between the time zone of the office a patient is located in and the time zone of the user requesting the report. User in Oklahoma requested an Active Patient Summary report for patients from 10/16/2014-10/31/2014. The report left out a patient from the Islands hospice that was admitted very late on 10/31. It seems the report filters based on the requesting user's time zone, but not based upon the time zone off the office the patient is located in.

https://umbrella.consoloservices.com/cached_files/65a988497193a15595b642ab3e143055
The report does not include this patient from the Islands hospice:
https://umbrella.consoloservices.com/patients/224519/care_level_changes
fields.summary: #13883 Patient Time Zone in reports (advantage)

comments.body:
Dave, after looking into this, I've determined that the Active Patient Summary doesn't work work well with the timezone differences. We are supposed to store the date (without timezone) in the care level change and use that, but generalizations don't do that.

Fortunately, that is going to be fixed with the new and improved generalizations based off billing demographics. I bet this works in sigma or staging already.

My advice is to not do anything about this, since we already have a fix for it. We could have to support staff test this in staging and sigma to see if its correct.

got it...   thanks
I will ask them to support... moving it to me for now
